\subsection{Arithmetic}

Consider a sequence $d_0^1$, $d_0^2$, $d_0^3$, $d_0^4$,  \ldots\ with nested differences to n$^{th}$ level.
\vspace{ 12pt }

\begin{tikzpicture}
  \small
\draw (0,3) -- (0.5,2.5) node[at start, above] {$d_0^1$} -- (1,3) node[at end, above] {$d_0^2$} -- (1.5,2.5) -- (2,3) node[at end, above] {$d_0^3$} -- (2.5, 2.5) -- (3, 3) node[at end, above] {$d_0^4$};
\node[above] at (3.5,3) {$\ldots$} ;
\draw (0.5,2) -- (1,1.5) node[at start, above] {$d_1^1$} -- (1.5,2) node[at end, above] {$d_1^2$} -- (2, 1.5) -- (2.5, 2) node[at end, above] {$d_1^3$};
\node[above] at (4,2) {$1^{st}$ level  } ;
\node[above] at (3,2) {$\ldots$} ;
\node[below] at (1,1.5) {$d_2^1$} ;
\node[below] at (2,1.5) {$d_2^2$} ;
\node[below] at (2.5,1.3) {$\ldots$} ;
\node[below] at (1.5,0.75) {$\ldots$} ;
\node[below] at (1.5,0.5) {$\ldots$} ;
\node at (3,0.5) {$n^{th}$ level  } ;
\end{tikzpicture}

Then, let us arrange the above as follows:

\begin{tikzpicture}
\draw (0,5) -- (0.5,4.5) node[at start, above] {$d_0^1$} -- (1,5) node[at end, above] {$d_1^1$} -- (1.5,4.5) -- (2,5) node[at end, above] {$d_2^1$}; 
\node[gray] at (3,5) {$\ldots$} ;
\draw (0.5,4) -- (1,3.5) node[at start, above] {$d_0^2$} -- (1.5,4) node[at end, above] {$d_1^2$} ;
\node[gray] at (3.5,4) {$\ldots$} ;
\draw[gray] (1.5,4) -- (2,3.5) -- (2.5,4) node[at end, above] {$d_2^2$}; 
\node[above] at (1,3) {$d_0^3$} ;
\node[gray] at (4,3) {$\ldots$} ;
\draw[gray] (1,3)-- (1.5,2.5) -- (2,3) node[at end, above] {$d_1^3$} -- (2.5,2.5) -- (3,3) node[at end, above] {$d_2^3$}; 
\draw[gray] (1.5,2) -- (2,1.5) node [at start, above] { $d_0^4$ } -- (2.5, 2) node [at end, above] {$d_1^4$} -- (3,1.5) -- (3.5, 2) node [at end, above] {$d_2^4$};
\node[gray] at (4.5,2) {$\ldots$} ;
\node[below, gray] at (2,1) {$\ldots$} ;
\node[below, gray] at (3,1) {$\ldots$} ;
\node[below, gray] at (4,1) {$\ldots$} ;
\end{tikzpicture}
\vspace{12pt}

In this interpretation, the $d_0^n$ elements are the n$^{th}$ terms of the sequence. The $d_1^{n}$ elements represent the first level differences, $d_2^{n}$ represents the second level differences, and so on. Therefore, the following relations are true:
\pagebreak

\[ d_0^3 = d_0^2 + d_1^2\]
\[ d_0^2 = d_0^1 + d_1^1\]
\[ d_1^2 = d_1^1 + d_1^1\]

So, the lines represent sum operation in case of arithmetic sequences. Hence, for any term $d_0^n$, its value is given by
(No of $d_0^1$s in $d_0^n$)$\cdot d_0^1 + $ (No of $d_1^1$s in $d_0^n$)$\cdot d_1^1 + $ 

